# m5_weapon_held.shot — M5 P11
#
# Verifies the per-weapon visible-art runtime (P11):
#   - Pulse Rifle is visibly distinct from Mass Driver / Sidearm at
#     a glance (silhouette length scales with the weapon sprite size).
#   - Two-handed weapons drive L_HAND toward the foregrip pose target;
#     one-handed (Sidearm / Frag Grenades) leaves L_HAND dangling.
#   - BTN_FIRE_SECONDARY (RMB) flickers the inactive slot's weapon at
#     R_HAND for ~3 ticks before reverting.
#   - Active-slot swap (BTN_SWAP / Q) replaces the visible weapon and
#     drops the foregrip pose for a one-handed secondary.
#   - Muzzle flash sprite renders additively at the per-weapon muzzle.
#
# At P11 ship `assets/sprites/weapons.png` doesn't exist, so the
# fallback line draws — but the line's length is per-weapon
# (`draw_w * 0.7`) so visible distinctness still reads on the contact
# sheet. When the atlas eventually lands (P16) the same shots will
# show real sprites without script changes.
#
# Run:
#   ./soldut --shot tests/shots/m5_weapon_held.shot
# Output:
#   build/shots/m5_weapon_held/*.png + weapon_sheet.png

window 1280 720
seed   11 11
out    build/shots/m5_weapon_held

# Player Trooper holding Pulse Rifle (two-handed, foregrip-driving)
# + Frag Grenades (one-handed). Aim slightly up-right so the weapon
# is visible against the floor tiles.
loadout Trooper "Pulse Rifle" "Frag Grenades" Light Standard
spawn_at 640 984
mouse    1000 360

# Reference row: same chassis, four different primaries — visibly
# different barrel lengths under the fallback line render. Mass Driver
# is the longest weapon (96 px → 67 px barrel line); Sidearm is the
# shortest (28 px → 20 px); the others sit in between.
extra_chassis Trooper  240 984 "Mass Driver"
extra_chassis Trooper  400 984 "Microgun"
extra_chassis Trooper  900 984 "Rail Cannon"
extra_chassis Trooper 1080 984 "Sidearm"

# Let the Verlet solver settle each chassis into its standing pose.
at  60 shot pristine_pulse_rifle

# LMB single-shot — captures the Pulse Rifle muzzle-flash window.
at  68 press fire
at  69 release fire
at  70 shot lmb_fire_flash

# RMB BTN_FIRE_SECONDARY one-shot. Pulse cooldown is 110 ms (~7
# ticks), so the active LMB path bails for several ticks; RMB still
# fires Frag Grenades because shared `fire_cooldown` only blocks
# fresh fires within the 110 ms window of the LMB shot — wait until
# 90 (~22 ticks after LMB fire) so the shared cooldown is clear.
at  90 press fire_secondary
at  91 release fire_secondary
# Capture during the 3-tick render flicker window — secondary's
# Frag Grenade sprite (16×16) replaces the rifle at R_HAND.
at  92 shot rmb_throw_flicker
# After the window: rifle returns to R_HAND.
at  98 shot rmb_after_flicker

# Active-slot swap: Pulse Rifle → Frag Grenades. One-handed weapon
# means the foregrip pose target stays unset → L_HAND falls back to
# the M1 dangle behavior. Verifiable via the weapon being smaller
# AND the L_HAND particle sitting noticeably lower than the foregrip
# would have placed it.
at 130 press swap
at 131 release swap
at 145 shot frag_active_dangle

# Swap back: rifle returns, foregrip re-engages on next tick's
# build_pose pass.
at 165 press swap
at 166 release swap
at 180 shot pulse_active_again

# Composite all six shots into one sheet — easier to eyeball the
# visible-art differences side-by-side.
contact_sheet weapon_sheet cols 3 cell 320 180

at 200 end
